ğŸ“ŒğŸ“Œ"Superman" is a song by American rapper Eminem from his fourth studio album, The Eminem Show (2002), featuring guest vocals from his frequent collaborator, singer Dina Rae. Written by Eminem, Jeff Bass and Steve King, the song was released as the third single from The Eminem Show on January 21, 2003, in the United States only. It peaked at number 15 on the Billboard Hot 100 chart on the issue dated March 15, 2003, and received 2Ã— Platinum certification by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA). Background "Superman" is about the rocky relationships and promiscuous nature of the girls Eminem has had in his life and how he plans to deal with it. In his 2008 autobiography, The Way I Am, Eminem revealed that the song is, to an extent, about his alleged relationship with Mariah Carey.[1] "Superman" is very similar to Eminem's song "Drug Ballad" and D12's song "Pimp Like Me". In a 2021 interview with Raaj Bundles of SideShowRaaj, Dina Rae revealed that Carey originally sung the hook for "Superman" before being replaced with herself, due to personal conflicts between Eminem and Carey.[2] Critical reception Entertainment Weekly editor described "In the creepy-crawly, mesmerizing 'Superman', he depicts himself as both sexual predator and commitment-phobic single guy."[3] HipHopDX named the production "the southern bounce", lyrics as dealing with groupies and called the chorus "cheesy".[4] Steve Juon described the song's rap style: "'Superman' features Eminem playing with his flow in a stuttered cadence, but he's done the gimmick before and his beat on this one inspires only partial attention to his flow."[5] Rolling Stone concluded that his divorce fuels the slow Southern bounce of the hypermisogynist "Superman".[6]

(a) What is a lesson plan? A lesson plan is a guide that teachers use to organize what theyâ€™re going to teach during a class. Itâ€™s like a roadmap that helps make sure lessons are clear, structured, and meet the learning goals for students. A good lesson plan breaks down what topics will be covered, how long each part will take, what materials are needed, and how the lesson will be delivered. It helps keep everything on track and ensures that the teacher knows what the objectives are for the lesson. (b) What are the parts of a lesson plan? A lesson plan typically includes several key parts: 	1.	Objectives: These are the learning goals, basically what students should know or be able to do by the end of the lesson. 	2.	Materials: A list of everything needed for the lesson (textbooks, handouts, technology, etc.). 	3.	Procedure: This is the step-by-step outline of how the lesson will be taught, including the introduction, main activities, and the conclusion. 	4.	Assessment: How the teacher will check if students have understood the material (quizzes, discussions, assignments). 	5.	Timing: A breakdown of how much time will be spent on each activity. 	6.	Reflection: Some lesson plans also include space for teachers to reflect on how the lesson went and what could be improved next time. (c) What are the types of lesson plan? There are different types of lesson plans depending on the purpose or style of the lesson: 	1.	Daily Lesson Plans: These are the most common and cover what will be taught in one class period or one day. 	2.	Unit Lesson Plans: These plans cover a longer time frame, like a week or a whole unit, and break it down into smaller lessons. 	3.	Activity-Based Plans: Focus on hands-on activities or projects as the main way to teach the material. 	4.	Inquiry-Based Plans: These encourage students to ask questions and explore topics more independently, often used in science or research-based subjects. Each type of lesson plan is designed to meet different teaching and learning needs, but they all serve the same basic purpose of organizing and structuring the teaching process.
